His reason- ing is this: Princes who gain great victories, and triumph over their enemies‚ almost equal the godS‚ and acquire inimortal renown: in like manner, they whose merit recommends them to the favour of these true images of the deity, are by this raised above the rest of their species. The poet here both makes his court to Augustus, and defends the part he had himself chosen; for, in the first satire of the second book, he tells us, that envy itself must own he had lived in reputation with the great.—-35. Principibus viris. “The great.'’ Principibus is here used in a more extensive signification than ordinary, and indicates the great, the powerful, the noble, &ze—36. Non cuivis homini contingit adire Corinthum. A proverbial form of expression, and said of things that are arduous and perilous, and which it is not the fortune of every one to sui-mount. Horace, by using this adage, intends to show that all people have not talents proper for succeeding in a court, while he seeks at the same time to raise the glory of those who have courage to attempt, and address to conquer the difficulties there.
